  <h2>Entering the Giant Digital City</h2>
  <p>
    Imagine walking into a massive, magical city that stretches as far as the eye can see. In this city, there are endless toy stores to explore, libraries with every book ever written, theaters playing your favorite videos, and parks where you can play games with kids from across the globe. That is exactly what the internet is—a giant, wonderful virtual city.
  </p>
  <p>
    But just like in a real city, while there are lots of fun places to explore and friendly people to meet, there are also busy streets where you need to look both ways, and areas where you should be careful. <strong>Online safety</strong> is your set of digital street-smarts. It teaches you how to protect your personal information, spot tricks, be kind, and have a fantastic time online without getting into trouble.
  </p>

  <h2>Rule 1: Keep Your Secret Identity Secret!</h2>
  <p>
    Have you ever noticed that superheroes wear masks to protect their real names and where they live? When you are online, you need to protect your "secret identity" too! Programmers call this **Personal Information**. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Personal information is any detail that can help a stranger online figure out who you are, where you live, or what school you go to. You should never share these details in chat rooms, game lobbies, or on social media profile pages:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🏠 <strong>Your physical location:</strong> Your home address, town, or street name.</li>
    <li>🏫 <strong>Your school details:</strong> The name of your school, your school mascot, or even photos of you wearing your school uniform (which has a logo that gives away your location!).</li>
    <li>📞 <strong>Contact details:</strong> Your phone number, email address, or your parents' work numbers.</li>
    <li>🔑 <strong>Your passwords:</strong> Never share your passwords with anyone, not even your best friend! (It is okay if your parents know them, though).</li>
    <li>📅 <strong>Your birthday:</strong> Telling people your exact birth date and year.</li>
  </ul>
  <blockquote>
    <strong>The T-Shirt Rule:</strong> Before you post a comment, photo, or username online, ask yourself: "Would I print this information on a T-shirt and wear it while walking down a busy street?" If the answer is no, do not type it online!
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Rule 2: The Online Stranger Danger Rule</h2>
  <p>
    When you play multiplayer games like Roblox, Minecraft, or Fortnite, you can chat with other players. It is fun to team up, but you must remember: **people online are not always who they say they are.**
  </p>
  <p>
    Because you cannot see the person behind the screen, someone might tell you they are a 10-year-old kid who loves the same cartoons as you, but they could actually be a grown-up trying to trick you. This is sometimes called **catfishing**.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Never make offline plans:</strong> Never agree to meet up in the real world with someone you only met online. </li>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Keep camera safety in mind:</strong> Never send photos or videos of yourself, your family, or your home to anyone you do not know in real life.</li>
    <li>⚠️ <strong>Use game-name safety:</strong> Never use your real name as your gaming username. Choose something creative, like <em>PixelNinja99</em> or <em>CookieMonsterCoder</em>.</li>
    <li>✅ <strong>Tell a grown-up:</strong> If anyone online ever asks you to keep a secret, asks you uncomfortable questions, or makes you feel weird, tell a parent, teacher, or trusted adult immediately.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Rule 3: Create an Unbreakable Password Lock</h2>
  <p>
    Imagine putting all your favorite toys in a treasure chest, but locking it with a lock that opens if someone guesses the word "toy." That wouldn't be very safe! Hackers use fast computer programs to guess weak passwords in seconds.
  </p>
  <p>
    To protect your game accounts and profiles, you need a **strong password**. A great way to do this is to use a **Passphrase**—a combination of random words that are easy for you to remember, but impossible for a computer to guess:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>📏 <strong>Make it long:</strong> Use at least 12 to 15 characters.</li>
    <li>🔤 <strong>Mix it up:</strong> Use uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols (like <code>!</code>, <code>@</code>, or <code>#</code>).</li>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Avoid the obvious:</strong> Do not use your name, your pet's name, your birthday, or simple sequences like <code>123456</code> or <code>qwerty</code>.</li>
    <li>🐒 <strong>Passphrase Example:</strong> Instead of using <code>monkey123</code>, try something like <code>BlueMonkeyEatsSpaghetti9!</code>. It's funny, easy to picture in your head, and would take a computer years to crack!</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Rule 4: Spotting Online Scams and Trapdoors</h2>
  <p>
    Have you ever seen a pop-up ad that says: "Congratulations! You won a FREE iPad! Click here to claim!" or a website promising "Get 1,000,000 Free Robux or V-Bucks instantly!"?
  </p>
  <p>
    These are called **scams**, and they are digital traps. Scammers write these to trick you into clicking links that download computer viruses (malware) or steal your game accounts. Here are the most common scams kids run into:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>💰 <strong>Free Currency Generators:</strong> Websites that ask for your password or username in exchange for free game money. **They will steal your account.** Real game currencies can only be bought through official game stores.</li>
    <li>😱 <strong>The Fake Virus Warning:</strong> A scary pop-up screen that flashes red and says "Your computer has a virus! Click here to clean it!" This is a trick to make you download bad software. If this happens, simply close the browser tab.</li>
    <li>🎣 <strong>Phishing emails:</strong> Messages that pretend to be from official companies like YouTube, Roblox, or Apple, asking you to click a link to "fix your account." The link leads to a fake login page that records your password.</li>
  </ul>
  <blockquote>
    <strong>The Golden Rule of Scams:</strong> If something online sounds too good to be true, it is almost certainly a trick!
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Rule 5: Be an Upstander, Not a Bystander</h2>
  <p>
    Because people sit behind screens, they sometimes say mean things online that they would never say face-to-face. This is called **cyberbullying**. Cyberbullying can happen in game chats, social media comments, or group text messages.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you see someone being bullied online, don't just stand by and watch (being a bystander). You can help stop it by being an **upstander**:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Do not join in:</strong> Never like, share, or reply to mean comments. Bullying thrives on attention.</li>
    <li>Block the person immediately. Every major game and app has a "Block" button.</li>
    <li>Use the report tool built into the app or game to flag the mean behavior to the moderators.</li>
    <li>Take screenshots of the mean messages to show a teacher or parent.</li>
    <li>Send a private message to the person who was bullied to let them know you are their friend and that the bully's words aren't true.</li>
  </ul>

