  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-section">
    <h3>Is it safe to share my username with a school classmate?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes! It is perfectly safe to share your gaming usernames with friends, classmates, and family members you know in real life. That is how you connect and play games together. Just make sure your username itself doesn't contain private info like your phone number or home address.
    </p>

    <h3>What should I do if my computer starts behaving weirdly?</h3>
    <p>
      If your computer suddenly starts opening lots of random pop-up ads, runs very slowly, or changes your homepage to a strange website, it might have downloaded malware (a computer virus). Don't panic! Tell a parent or teacher right away so they can run an antivirus scan to clean up the files.
    </p>

    <h3>What is the 20-20-20 rule?</h3>
    <p>
      Staring at screens for hours can cause eye strain and headaches. The 20-20-20 rule is a simple trick to protect your eyes: Every 20 minutes, look away from your screen and look at an object that is at least 20 feet away for at least 20 seconds. This gives your eye muscles a chance to rest and relax!
    </p>

    <h3>Is it okay to play games on public Wi-Fi?</h3>
    <p>
      Public Wi-Fi networks (like the ones in coffee shops, libraries, or airports) are open to everyone, which means they are not very secure. It is fine to use them to look up info or watch videos, but avoid logging into important accounts or typing passwords on public networks unless you are using a secure connection (look for the HTTPS padlock!).
    </p>
  </div>

